    <subsection><title>Fifth Grade</title>
    <assemblage>
            <title>Context 1: Solar energy and soils, elements needed to grow our food </title>
            <p>In this context, students will relate to how Indigenous peoples connect to the sun and use solar energy, including through renewable energy technology like photovoltaics. Students can relate science standards to the need for healthy soils for farming. </p> 
       </assemblage> 
    
      <example> <title>Standard 5-ESS1-1</title>
        <p>
          Description: Support an argument that differences in the apparent brightness of the sun compared to other stars is due to their relative distances from the Earth.
        </p>
        <p><em>In-class or take home exercise:</em>Introduce students to photovoltaics by discussing how some Native communities in the Southwest rely on solar energy technology to provide electricity in their homes. Show students the Native Renewables website (<url href="https://www.nativerenewables.org/" />). Download and pass out the zine created by Native Renewables that explains photovoltaics (<url href="https://static1.squarespace.com/static/5f491be9a82eed6a01fd24ac/t/6018a18e281db443ae79bb0e/1612226961043/Solar%2BMinizine%2Bv14.pdf" />). 
        </p>
        <p><em>Questions:</em>What are ways you use electricity in your homes? What happens when your home doesn’t have electricity? Why do photovoltaics only work during the day? Can photovoltaics work at night using light from other stars? 
        </p>
      </example>
    
      <example> <title>Standard 5-ESS1-2</title>
        <p>
          Description: Represent data in graphical displays to reveal patterns of daily changes in length and direction of shadows, day and night, and the seasonal appearance of some stars in the night sky.
        </p>
        <p><em>Take home exercise:</em> Introduce students to passive solar energy by handing out this handout on passive solar home design in NM (<url href="https://www.nmsolar.org/wp-content/uploads/2017/04/Passive-Solar-Design.pdf" />). 
        </p>
        <p>Ask students to walk around their home, village, and neighborhoods to identify how some homes make use of passive solar energy.
        </p>
      </example>
    
      <example> <title>Standard 5-ESS2-1</title>
        <p>
          Description: Develop a model using an example to describe ways the geosphere, biosphere, hydrosphere, and/or
atmosphere interacts.
        </p>
        <p><em>Questions:</em> How do you interact with each of the spheres? What sphere is your home built on and the materials used for your home built on? What sphere does your food come from? How does the sun interact with each sphere?
        </p>
      </example>
    
      <example> <title>Standard 5-ESS2-2</title>
        <p>
          Description: Describe and graph the amounts and percentages of water and fresh water in various reservoirs to provide
evidence about the distribution of water on Earth.
        </p>
        <p><em>In-class exercise:</em> Discuss with students how water is distributed in New Mexico. Refer to the FAQs about water page of the NM Bureau of Geology and Mineral Resources: <url href="https://geoinfo.nmt.edu/faq/water/home.html"/>). Relate to the global distribution of rainfall (<url href="https://www.climate-charts.com/World-Climate-Maps.html" />) and discuss how NM is in an arid climate and we get a lot of solar radiation that easily evaporates our rainfall. Thus, we have less surface water and rely more on groundwater compared to other areas in the world.
        </p>
      </example>
    
      <example> <title>Standard 5-ESS3-1</title>
        <p>
          Description: Obtain and combine information about ways individual communities use science ideas to protect the Earth’s resources and environment.
        </p>
        <p><em>Take home or in-class exercise:</em> Introduce students to the NM Tribal Resilience Action Network by showing this YouTube video that discusses how Pueblos and Tribes in NM are addressing climate change: <video youtube="eRwiJaz2n14"/>
        </p>
        <p>Also, refer to the Eight Northern Indian Pueblos, Inc.-Office of Environmental Technical Assistance website (<url href="http://enipc-oeta.org/home.htm"/>) to discuss how Pueblos are addressing other environmental issues. </p>
      </example>
    
      <example> <title>Standard 5-LS1-1</title>
        <p>
          Description: Support an argument that plants get the materials they need for growth chiefly from air and water.
        </p>
        <p><em>Take home or in-class exercise:</em> Invite a Pueblo farmer to talk to students about Pueblo farming practices or ask students to talk to a family or community member about how the work they do in their fields to help their crops grow. </p>
      </example>
    
      <example> <title>Standard 5-LS2-1</title>
        <p>
          Description: Develop a model to describe the movement of matter among plants, animals, decomposers, and the
environment.
        </p>
        <p><em>In-class exercise:</em> Introduce students to the role of soil in decomposing plant and animal matter and other environmental functions by showing this YouTube video about soil health in NM: <url href="https://www.nmhealthysoil.org/2021/06/14/soil-care-is-climate-repair/"/>. </p>
      </example>
    
      <example> <title>Standard 5-PS1-1</title>
        <p>
          Description: Develop a model to describe that matter is made of particles too small to be seen.
        </p>
        <p><em>Questions:</em> What are photons? How are photons from the Sun used to generate electricity?</p>
        <p> <em>External resource:</em> How a PV Cell works: <url href="https://www.solarschools.net/knowledge-bank/renewable-energy/solar/how-a-pv-cell-works" />
        </p>
      </example>
    
      <example> <title>Standard 5-PS1-2</title>
        <p>
          Description: Measure and graph quantities to provide evidence that regardless of the type of change that occurs when
heating, cooling, or mixing substances, the total weight of matter is conserved.
        </p>
        <p><em>In-class exercise:</em> Materials needed: scale or balance, jars with lids, thermometer, marker, soil collected from different natural local locations.</p>
<p>
Fill a jar halfway full with water and close tightly with a lid. Stick a thermometer in the water and weigh the jar. Record the weight and the temperature. Then, stick the jar outside to be warmed by the sun. After several minutes, record the temperature and weight. </p>
<p>
Next, use the jar and water to conduct soil texture activity (<url href="https://www.soils4kids.org/files/s4k/soil-texture-experiment.pdf"/>). Tell students where soils were collected from so they can figure out the soil texture in those locations. </p>
<p>
Refer to the “Background Agricultural Connections” portion of this website (<url href="https://agclassroom.org/matrix/lesson/print/365/"/>)
 to talk to students about the importance of knowing soil texture for farming. Next, mix two different types of soil samples and redo the soil texture analysis.
        </p>
      </example>
    
      <example> <title>Standard 5-PS1-3</title>
        <p>
          Description: Make observations and measurements to identify materials based on their properties.
        </p>
        <p><em>In-class exercise:</em> Materials needed: scale or balance, jars with lids, thermometer, marker, soil collected from different natural local locations.</p>
<p>
Fill a jar halfway full with water and close tightly with a lid. Stick a thermometer in the water and weigh the jar. Record the weight and the temperature. Then, stick the jar outside to be warmed by the sun. After several minutes, record the temperature and weight. </p>
<p>
Next, use the jar and water to conduct soil texture activity (<url href="https://www.soils4kids.org/files/s4k/soil-texture-experiment.pdf"/>). Tell students where soils were collected from so they can figure out the soil texture in those locations. </p>
<p>
Refer to the “Background Agricultural Connections” portion of this website (<url href="https://agclassroom.org/matrix/lesson/print/365/"/>)
 to talk to students about the importance of knowing soil texture for farming. Next, mix two different types of soil samples and redo the soil texture analysis.
        </p>
      </example>
    
      <example> <title>Standard 5-PS1-4</title>
        <p>
          Description: Conduct an investigation to determine whether the mixing of two or more substances results in new
substances.
        </p>
        <p><em>In-class exercise:</em> Materials needed: scale or balance, jars with lids, thermometer, marker, soil collected from different natural local locations.</p>
<p>
Fill a jar halfway full with water and close tightly with a lid. Stick a thermometer in the water and weigh the jar. Record the weight and the temperature. Then, stick the jar outside to be warmed by the sun. After several minutes, record the temperature and weight. </p>
<p>
Next, use the jar and water to conduct soil texture activity (<url href="https://www.soils4kids.org/files/s4k/soil-texture-experiment.pdf"/>). Tell students where soils were collected from so they can figure out the soil texture in those locations. </p>
<p>
Refer to the “Background Agricultural Connections” portion of this website (<url href="https://agclassroom.org/matrix/lesson/print/365/"/>)
 to talk to students about the importance of knowing soil texture for farming. Next, mix two different types of soil samples and redo the soil texture analysis.
        </p>
      </example>
    
      <example> <title>Standard 5-PS2-1</title>
        <p>
          Description: Support an argument that the gravitational force exerted by Earth on objects is directed down.
        </p>
        <p><em>In-class exercise:</em> Conduct this activity on soil infiltration (<url href="https://sndl.ucmerced.edu/files/MHWG/Field/Southern_Sierra_CZO_KREW/Education_and_Outreach/Activities/Activity3_SoilInfiltrationandTexture.pdf"/>)</p>
<p>
Relate this activity to how when water is applied to crop fields the water moves into the soil due to gravity.
        </p>
      </example>
    
      <example> <title>Standard 5-PS3-1</title>
        <p>
          Description: Use models to describe that energy in animals’ food (used for body repair, growth, motion, and to maintain
body warmth) was once energy from the sun.
        </p>
        <p><em>In-class exercise:</em> Relate concepts to farming and gardening practices used to grow food for Pueblo people. Refer to the “Pueblo Farming Methods for your Resilient Garden” webpage and videos embedded on the webpage (<url href="https://thegrownetwork.com/pueblo-farming-methods/"/>).
        </p>
      </example>
    </subsection>
    <!-- Sixth Grade -->
    <subsection><title>Sixth Grade</title>
    <assemblage>
            <title>Context 1: Chaco Canyon and Climate Change </title>
            <p>This context will relate the following standards to climate change and Chaco Canyon, including the history of Chaco Canyon, astronomy and architecture, ties to climate change, and current oil and gas development in the area. Some evidence shows that the peoples who lived in Chaco Canyon may have been impacted by past climate change or a megadrought (<url href="http://pastglobalchanges.org/download/docs/magazine/2016-2/PAGESmagazine_2016%282%29_64-65_Betancourt.pdf"/>). More context on Chaco Canyon history can be found here: <url href="https://www.nps.gov/chcu/learn/historyculture/index.htm"/>. More information on oil and gas development in the Chaco Canyon region can be found here: <url href="https://www.sanjuancitizens.org/chaco"/>.  </p> 
       </assemblage> 
    
      <example> <title>Standard MS-ESS1-1</title>
        <p>
          Description: Develop and use a model of the Earth-sun-moon system to describe the cyclic patterns of lunar phases, eclipses of the sun and moon, and seasons.
        </p>
        <p><em>In-class or take home exercise:</em>Describe how the Chaco Canyon sun dagger and architecture of buildings are related to Earth-sun-moon phases. 
        </p>
          <p>Refer to information on this handout on how lunar and solar cycles were recorded by the Chaco Canyon Sun Dagger: <url href="http://www.bullfrogfilms.com/guides/sdguide.pdf"/>
          </p>
        <p><em>External resource:</em>“The Solstice Project” (<url href="https://www.solsticeproject.org/"/>) provides resources on astronomy at Chaco Canyo 
        </p>
      </example>
        
      <example> <title>Standard MS-ESS1-2</title>
        <p>
          Description: Develop and use a model to describe the role of gravity in the motions within galaxies and the solar system.
        </p>
        <p><em>In-class or take home exercise:</em> Discuss how gravity from giant planets Jupiter and Saturn can change the shape of Earth’s orbit leading to some cycles of climate change. Read more here: <url href="https://climate.nasa.gov/news/2948/milankovitch-orbital-cycles-and-their-role-in-earths-climate/"/>
<p>These changes are not the cause of the current climate change which is linked primarily to carbon emissions.</p>
<p>Also discuss how the moon orbits the Earth due to Earth’s gravitational pull and the relative size of the Earth to the Moon. </p>
        </p>
      </example>
        
      <example> <title>Standard MS-ESS1-3</title>
        <p>
          Description: Analyze and interpret data to determine scale properties of objects in the solar system.
        </p>
        <p><em>In-class or take home exercise:</em> Discuss how gravity from giant planets Jupiter and Saturn can change the shape of Earth’s orbit leading to some cycles of climate change. Read more here: <url href="https://climate.nasa.gov/news/2948/milankovitch-orbital-cycles-and-their-role-in-earths-climate/"/>
<p>These changes are not the cause of the current climate change which is linked primarily to carbon emissions.</p>
<p>Also discuss how the moon orbits the Earth due to Earth’s gravitational pull and the relative size of the Earth to the Moon. </p>
        </p>
      </example>
        
      <example> <title>Standard MS-ESS1-4</title>
        <p>
          Description: Construct a scientific explanation based on evidence from rock strata for how the geologic time scale is used to organize Earth's 4.6-billion-year-old history.
        </p>
        <p><em>In-class:</em> Explore the geologic strata of the San Juan Basin which underlie Chaco Canyon and contain the oil and gas resources that are being extracted. Discuss the ages that range from 40-80 million years of the younger strata lying closer to the surface and the deeper older strata. Discuss the geologic processes that explain how the sediments were deposited.
<p><em>External resource:</em> Geologic tour of Navajo Lake State Park <url href="https://geoinfo.nmt.edu/tour/state/navaho_lake/home.html"/>
</p>
        </p>
      </example>
      
        <example> <title>Standard MS-ESS2-2</title>
        <p>
          Description: Construct an explanation based on evidence for how geoscience processes have changed Earth's surface at varying time and spatial scales.
        </p>
        <p><em>In-class exercise:</em> Explore the geologic strata of the San Juan Basin which underlie Chaco Canyon and contain the oil and gas resources that are being extracted. Discuss the ages that range from 40-80 million years of the younger strata lying closer to the surface and the deeper older strata. Discuss the geologic processes that explain how the sediments were deposited.
<p><em>External resource:</em> Geologic tour of Navajo Lake State Park <url href="https://geoinfo.nmt.edu/tour/state/navaho_lake/home.html"/>
</p>
        </p>
      </example>
     
      <example> <title>Standard MS-ESS2-3</title>
        <p>
          Description: Analyze and interpret data on the distribution of fossils and rocks, continental shapes, and seafloor structures to provide evidence of the past plate motions.
        </p>
        <p><em>In-class exercise:</em> Introduce students to paleontology of the Bisti Wilderness (<url href="http://www.aztecnm.com/recreation/bisti.html"/>, <url href="https://discovernavajo.com/bisti-badlands"/>). </p> 
            
<p><em>Questions:</em> What kind of climate/environment of the plants and animals that are fossilized in the Bisti Wilderness represent? How different is it from the current climate/environment? “De-Na-Zin” means “crane” in the Navajo language and is the other name for the Bisti Wilderness area. Why do you think Navajo people named this area after the crane? What is the word for crane in your Native language? </p>     
      </example>
      
      <example> <title>Standard MS-ESS2-4</title>
        <p>
          Description: Develop a model to describe the cycling of water through Earth's systems driven by energy from the sun and the force of gravity.
        </p>  
  
        <p><em>In-class exercise:</em> Discuss the importance of groundwater in NM because we rely on it during times of drought and how groundwater is depleted because it takes a long time to recharge. Refer to the USGS website on groundwater: <url href="https://www.usgs.gov/special-topic/water-science-school/science/groundwater-what-groundwater?qt-science_center_objects=0#qt-science_center_objects"/>.
        </p>
          </example> 

      <example> <title>Standard MS-ESS2-5</title>
        <p>
          Description: Collect data to provide evidence for how the motions and complex interactions of air masses result in changes in weather conditions.
        </p>
        <p><em>In-class exercise:</em> Discuss how changes in sea surface temperatures in the Pacific Ocean like El Nino and La Nina can affect weather and climate here in NM. Discuss how the Indigenous peoples living in Chaco may have been affected by a drought caused by La Nina: <url href="https://www.nature.com/scitable/knowledge/library/el-nino-s-grip-on-climate-25816069/"/>.
        </p>
      </example>
        
      <example> <title>Standard MS-ESS2-6</title>
        <p>
          Description: Develop and use a model to describe how unequal heating and rotation of the Earth cause patterns of atmospheric and oceanic circulation that determine regional climates.
        </p>
        <p><em>In-class exercise:</em> Discuss how Indigenous peoples understand how to live in the climate conditions of their homelands because of thousands of years of building relationships with their environments. Also discuss how Indigenous peoples have adapted to climate changes in the past: <url href="https://phys.org/news/2010-12-indigenous-peoples-climate.html"/>
        </p>
      </example>
        
      <example> <title>Standard MS-ESS3-5</title>
        <p>
          Description: Ask questions to clarify evidence of the factors that have caused the rise in global temperatures over the past century.
        </p>
        <p><em>In-class exercise:</em> Discuss how oil and gas drilling in Chaco Canyon and other places lead to additional greenhouse gas emissions and rising global temperatures.
        </p>
      </example>
        
      <example> <title>Standard MS-LS4-1</title>
        <p>
          Description: Analyze and interpret data for patterns in the fossil record that document the existence, diversity, extinction, and change of life forms throughout the history of life on Earth under the assumption that natural laws operate today as in the past.
        </p>
        <p><em>In-class exercise:</em> Discuss fossils found in the Bisti Wilderness: (<url href="http://www.aztecnm.com/recreation/bisti.html"/>, <url href="https://discovernavajo.com/bisti-badlands/"/>).
        </p>
        <p> <em>Questions:</em>What kind of climate/environment (seafloor) of the plants and animals that are fossilized in the Bisti Wilderness represent? How different is it from the current climate/environment? 
            “De-Na-Zin” means “crane” in the Navajo language and is the other name for the Bisti Wilderness area. Why do you think Navajo people named this area after the crane? What is the word for crane in your Native language? “De-Na-Zin” means “crane” in the Navajo language and is the other name for the Bisti Wilderness area. Why do you think Navajo people named this area after the crane? What is the word for crane in your Native language? </p>
<p>
What kind of environment did the Bisti Beast live in?
What modern animals might the Bisti Beast be related to?</p>     
      </example>
      
      <example> <title>Standard MS-LS4-2</title>
        <p>
          Description: Apply scientific ideas to construct an explanation for the anatomical similarities and differences among modern organisms and between modern and fossil organisms to infer evolutionary relationships.
        </p>
        <p><em>In-class exercise:</em> Discuss fossils found in the Bisti Wilderness: (<url href="http://www.aztecnm.com/recreation/bisti.html"/>, <url href="https://discovernavajo.com/bisti-badlands/"/>).
        </p>
        <p> <em>Questions:</em>What kind of climate/environment (seafloor) of the plants and animals that are fossilized in the Bisti Wilderness represent? How different is it from the current climate/environment? 
            “De-Na-Zin” means “crane” in the Navajo language and is the other name for the Bisti Wilderness area. Why do you think Navajo people named this area after the crane? What is the word for crane in your Native language? “De-Na-Zin” means “crane” in the Navajo language and is the other name for the Bisti Wilderness area. Why do you think Navajo people named this area after the crane? What is the word for crane in your Native language? </p>
<p>
What kind of environment did the Bisti Beast live in?
What modern animals might the Bisti Beast be related to?</p>     
      </example>
        
      <assemblage>
            <title>Context 2: Radioactive waste from mining and Los Alamos National Laboratory </title>
          <p>This context will help students relate these physics concepts to how Indigenous communities in NM have been impacted by uranium mining and nuclear activity in New Mexico.</p>
      </assemblage> 
    
      <example> <title>Standard MS-PS1-1</title>
        <p>
          Description: Develop models to describe the atomic composition of simple molecules and extended structures.  
        </p>
        <p><em>In-class or take home exercise:</em>Have students describe and model uranium. Help students research the history of uranium mining in NM and how it has impacted Pueblo and Navajo communities. 
        </p>
      </example>
      
      <example> <title>Standard MS-PS2-1</title>
        <p>
          Description: Apply Newton’s Third Law to design a solution to a problem involving the motion of two colliding objects.  
        </p>
        <p><em>In-class:</em>Discuss how the atomic bomb was developed using uranium to create a nuclear fission reaction involves the collision of two subatomic particles. Discuss how this led to nuclear research at Los Alamos National Labs and how this led to contamination of nearby Pueblo communities (<url href="https://sites.coloradocollege.edu/ejsw/2016/11/17/environmental-injustices-for-pueblo-communities-near-los-alamos-national-laboratory/"/>).
        </p>
      </example>
       
      <example> <title>Standard MS-PS2-2</title>
        <p>
          Description: Plan an investigation to provide evidence that the change in an object’s motion depends on the sum of the forces on the object and the mass of the object.  
        </p>
        <p><em>In-class:</em>Discuss how the atomic bomb was developed using uranium to create a nuclear fission reaction involves the collision of two subatomic particles. Discuss how this led to nuclear research at Los Alamos National Labs and how this led to contamination of nearby Pueblo communities (<url href="https://sites.coloradocollege.edu/ejsw/2016/11/17/environmental-injustices-for-pueblo-communities-near-los-alamos-national-laboratory/"/>).
        </p>
      </example>
