      <example> <title>Standard MS-LS4-3</title>
        <p>
          Description: Analyze displays of pictorial data to compare patterns of similarities in the embryological development across multiple species to identify relationships not evident in the fully formed anatomy.
        </p>
        <p><em>In-class exercise:</em> Discuss fish embryo development and compare traits of the different fish species found in the Rio Grande (<url href="https://aces.nmsu.edu/pubs/_circulars/CR653/welcome.html"/>).         
</p>
        <p><em>Questions</em> What kind of fish have you seen in the river or canals? What characteristics of the fish can you use to tell them apart? </p>
      </example>
        
      <example> <title>Standard MS-LS4-4</title>
        <p>
          Description: Construct an explanation based on evidence that describes how genetic variations of traits in a population increase some individuals’ probability of surviving and reproducing in a specific environment.
        </p>
        <p><em>In-class and take home exercise:</em> Many Indigenous peoples view animals as our four legged relatives. Concepts of “survival of the fittest” may not be in line with how relatives connect one another. Talk with students about how some animals like wolves (<url href="https://www.yellowstone.org/male-gray-wolves-protect-family-members-from-rival-packs/"/>) protect one another despite some individuals having more “weak” traits than others.         
</p>
        <p>Ask students to research how other animals found in this region protect each other.</p>
        <p>Ask students to reflect on how their tribe or Pueblo views their relationship to animals. </p>
      </example>
        
