        <example> <title>Standard MS-LS1-7</title>
        <p>
          Description: Develop a model to describe how food is rearranged through chemical reactions forming new molecules that support growth and/or release energy as this matter moves through an organism.
        </p>
            <p><em>In-class exercise:</em> </p> <p>Introduce students to bioaccumulation (<url href="https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=nNjhboUYM2c"/>). Describe how contaminants that are present in water in the Rio Grande and other streams can lead to bioaccumulation. </p>
        </example>
        
        <example> <title>Standard MS-LS1-8</title>
        <p>
          Description: Gather and synthesize information that sensory receptors respond to stimuli by sending messages to the brain for immediate behavior or storage as memories.
        </p>
            <p><em>In-class exercise:</em> </p> <p>Talk to students about what kind of memories they have when they “smell” rain or hear the river running.</p>
        </example>
        
        <example> <title>Standard MS-LS3-1</title>
        <p>
          Description: Develop and use a model to describe why  structural changes to genes (mutations) located on chromosomes may affect proteins and may result in harmful, beneficial, or neutral effects to the structure and function of the organism.
        </p>
            <p><em>In-class exercise:</em> </p> <p>Discuss with students about how contamination, and radioactive contamination in particular, could lead to harmful genetic effects. Talk with students about impacts of contamination of the Rio Grande and other streams from waste from Los Alamos National Laboratory (<url href="https://www.latimes.com/archives/la-xpm-2009-nov-01-na-radiation-newmexico1-story.html"/>).</p>
        </example>
        
        <example> <title>Standard MS-LS3-2</title>
        <p>
          Description: Develop and use a model to describe why asexual reproduction results in offspring with identical genetic information and sexual reproduction results in offspring with genetic variation.
        </p>
            <p><em>In-class exercise:</em> </p> <p>Talk about the asexual reproduction of aspen (<url href="https://www.nwf.org/Educational-Resources/Wildlife-Guide/Plants-and-Fungi/Quaking-Aspen"/>) which are commonly located near streams and rivers and in burn areas.</p>
