    <!-- Eighth Grade -->
    <subsection><title>Eighth Grade</title>
    <assemblage>
            <title>Context 1: Fires and Floods in our forested watersheds</title>
            <p>Wildfires and floods from monsoon rains are common occurrences in New Mexico. Fire crews from Pueblo communities have assisted in fighting many wildfires in New Mexico and across the West. More recently, Pueblo communities have been helping to restore cultural burning practices to help reduce the occurrences of catastrophic wildfires. Pueblo emergency management and natural resource departments are also working to understand flood risk due to wildfires and intense monsoon storms. Using this context will help students to connect concepts addressed in the following standards to issues Pueblo communities have been active in addressing. </p> 
       </assemblage> 
    
      <example> <title>Standard MS-ESS3-2 </title>
        <p>
          Description: Analyze and interpret data on natural hazards to forecast future catastrophic events andinform the development of technologies to mitigate their effects.
        </p>
        <p><em>External resource:</em> Hands on activity developed by the U.S. Geological Survey to learn about the size and frequency of floods: <url href="https://www.usgs.gov/educational-resources/size-and-occurrence-floods?qt-science_support_page_related_con=2#qt-science_support_page_related_con"/> 
        </p>
      </example>
        
      <example> <title>Standard MS-ESS3-3 </title>
        <p>
          Description: Apply scientific principles to design a method for monitoring and minimizing a human impact on the environment.
        </p>
        <p><em>In-class exercise:</em> Talk with students about how fire suppression by humans in the last century has led to a build up of fuels in forests leading to more larger and severe wildfires. Discuss how Indigenous peoples are revitalizing cultural burning practices which was used prior to the fire suppression era to reduce the build up of fuels (<url href="https://www.nature.org/en-us/magazine/magazine-articles/indigenous-controlled-burns-california/"/> and <url href="https://www.nature.org/en-us/membership-and-giving/donate-to-our-mission/gift-and-estate-planning/newsletter/forever-forests/"/>).  
        </p>
        <p><em>Questions:</em></p><p>How has fire suppression by humans impacted the environment? What are ways we can mitigate impacts of large wildfires without further fire suppression?</p>
      </example>
        
      <example> <title>Standard MS-ESS3-4 </title>
        <p>
          Description: Construct an argument supported by evidence for how increases in human population and per-capita consumption of natural resources impact Earth's systems.
        </p>
          <p><em>In-class exercise:</em> Talk with students about how fires are being burned in the Amazon for increased food production (<url href="https://www.cnn.com/2019/08/23/americas/brazil-beef-amazon-rainforest-fire-intl/index.html"/>). Discuss how these fires threaten the environment, climate, and Indigenous peoples in the Amazon (<url href="https://www.theatlantic.com/science/archive/2019/08/amazon-fires-indigenous-lands/596908/"/>). </p>
      </example>

      <example> <title>Standard MS-PS3-1 </title>
        <p>
          Description: Construct and interpret graphical displays of data to describe the relationships of kinetic energy to the mass of an object and to the speed of an object.
        </p>
          <p><em>In-class exercise:</em> Introduce students to flood hydrographs (<url href="https://www.internetgeography.net/topics/flood-hydrographs/"/>). Discuss how the timing and amount of peak streamflow shown in the hydrograph is related to the amount and intensity of rainfall and characteristics of the watershed. </p>
      </example>
        
      <example> <title>Standard MS-PS3-3 </title>
        <p>
          Description: Apply scientific principles to design, construct, and test a device that either minimizes or maximizes thermal energy transfer.
        </p>
          <p><em>In-class exercise:</em> Discuss how thermal energy is transferred during wildfires  (<url href="https://www.srs.fs.usda.gov/factsheet/pdf/fire-understanding.pdf"/>). Ask students to think about ways their villages or neighborhoods are designed to minimize fire damage or heat transfer. </p>
      </example>
        
      <example> <title>Standard MS-PS3-4 </title>
        <p>
          Description: Plan an investigation to determine the relationships among the energy transferred, the type of matter, the mass, and the change in the average kinetic energy of the particles as measured by the temperature of the sample.
        </p>
          <p><em>In-class exercise:</em> Discuss how thermal energy is transferred during wildfires  (<url href="https://www.srs.fs.usda.gov/factsheet/pdf/fire-understanding.pdf"/>). Ask students to think about ways their villages or neighborhoods are designed to minimize fire damage or heat transfer. </p>
      </example>
        
      <example> <title>Standard MS-PS3-5 </title>
        <p>
          Description: Construct, use, and present arguments to support the claim that when the kinetic energy of an object changes, energy is transferred to or from the object.
        </p>
          <p><em>In-class exercise:</em> Discuss with students how floods can lead to erosion of land/soils and problems associated with erosion. Ask students to look up videos on floods in NM (<video youtube="UYQYQA6QbJA"/>). Also ask students to reflect on any times they experienced flood events. Talk about how floods and erosion are exacerbated by wildfires (<url href="https://www.ready.gov/sites/default/files/Flood_After_Fire_Fact_Sheet.pdf"/>) and climate change. </p>
          <p>Discuss how Zuni Bowls, structures designed in Zuni Pueblo, can be used to control erosion (<url href="https://www.milkwood.net/2011/11/04/making-a-zuni-bowl-let-the-water-do-the-work/"/>).</p>
